  "prompt": "Is there a consensus that money laundering is against the law?",
  "response": "Yes, there is a global consensus that money laundering is against the law. Money laundering is the process of making illegally obtained money appear legitimate by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. It is a criminal offense in virtually all jurisdictions around the world.\n\n### Key Points:\n1. **International Agreements**: \n   - The **United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988)** was one of the first international efforts to combat money laundering.\n   - The **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**, established in 1989, sets global standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing. Its **40 Recommendations** provide a comprehensive framework for anti-money laundering (AML) and counter-terrorist financing (CTF) measures.\n\n2. **National Laws**:\n   - Most countries have enacted specific laws criminalizing money laundering. For example:\n     - In the **United States**, the **Bank Secrecy Act (1970)** and subsequent amendments, including the **USA PATRIOT Act (2001)**, establish strong anti-money laundering regulations.\n     - In the **European Union**, multiple directives, such as the **Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLD)**, require member states to implement robust AML frameworks.\n     - In **China**, the **Anti-Money Laundering Law of the People's Republic of China (2007)** criminalizes money laundering and mandates AML measures for financial institutions.\n\n3. **Penalties**:\n   - Penalties for money laundering can be severe, including hefty fines, imprisonment, and asset forfeiture. For example, in the U.S., money laundering offenses can result in fines up to $500,000 or twice the value of the laundered funds, and imprisonment for up to 20 years.\n\n4. **Global Enforcement**:\n   - Countries collaborate through organizations like **Interpol**, **Europol**, and bilateral agreements to investigate and prosecute money laundering activities across borders.\n\n### Conclusion:\nMoney laundering is universally recognized as a serious crime, and combating it is a priority for governments and international organizations. The global consensus on its illegality is reinforced by comprehensive legal frameworks, international cooperation, and enforcement efforts.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
